english:
  title: Record of the Hall of Tranquility
  author: Yi Kyu-bo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    It is the nature of the human heart to be gradually colored by circumstances. When the ear grows weary of cacophony and no longer hears the sound of clear waters, when the eye, accustomed to silk and splendor, fails to see the verdant hue of mountains, then a troubled and sluggish spirit begins to stir. Yet the beauty of mountains and waters is easily sought from afar but difficult to find near at hand. Thus, when the search within the city yields nothing, one ventures beyond the suburbs and borders; when even there it remains elusive, what can be done? Only those who yearn for retreat, who delight in self-perfection and stand aloof from the world, who wander freely in distant lands—only they may obtain it. Therefore, those who deeply love mountains and waters cannot enjoy the pleasures of wealth and rank, while those who are enamored with wealth and rank cannot attain the beauty of mountains and waters. Few indeed possess both.

    Now, my colleague Yu Gong, though dwelling in wealth and rank, sought to capture the essence of mountains and waters. Finding the imperial capital too distant, he chose a site beside the palace itself—the former residence of Zheng, an official of old. Once it was but barren gardens and crumbling villas, yet when Gong acquired it, he traced the veins of springs and built stone channels to capture them. For all drinking, washing, tea-brewing, and medicinal decoctions, the household depends upon this well. The overflow he gathered into a great pond, which he planted with lotus and water-chestnuts, where mandarin ducks and parrots now drift. Pavilions that capture the wind, halls that embrace the water, gardens of flowers, and groves of bamboo—each crafted with lavish design—until the beauty of thirty-six renowned peaks seems gathered within these walls. Why then must one retreat from the world and wander distant lands to taste the joy of mountains and waters?

    Gong pointed to a gentle rise and said, "This is my Tower of Watching the Palace." I marveled and replied, "How fitting is the name you have chosen! Your heart, devoted to matters of state, dwells ever near the Imperial countenance, yet still you find it insufficient. Your residence must be closer to the throne, and even this seems wanting. Thus you have built this tower to gaze upon your master's seat. Truly, this embodies the ancient saying: 'The sage's heart is never absent from the royal halls.'"

    Another height he called the Tower of Gazing at the Moon, and a structure with wings like a bird in flight he named the Pavilion of a Joyful Heart. He then asked me to name those places he had left unnamed. Thus I christened the garden Blossoms of Splendor, the well Jade's Fountain, the pond Mirror of Jade, and the bamboo pavilion Grove of Jade. All these names reflect their nature. And for the whole estate, I chose the name Tai—Tranquility.

    The hexagram Tai in the Book of Changes teaches: "When heaven and earth exchange their gifts, all things flourish; when ruler and subject are as one, their wills align." Now Gong, in this age when the way of the noble man ascends, serves his sovereign with united purpose, rendering assistance that allows all things to flow freely, heaven and earth to commune in harmony. Thus his body finds rest and his spirit finds peace, enjoying the leisure and contentment of one who dwells in paradise. Is it not fitting that I name his hall Tai—Tranquility?

    Before this, Gong commissioned the court official Yi Mi-su to compose a record of the Pavilion of a Joyful Heart, which was inscribed on silk and hung upon the pavilion's right side. He has now asked me to create this record to stand opposite on the left. So fond is he of the literary arts! Yi Mi-su is master of magnificent prose, depicting things with minute precision and thorough detail. Therefore I shall not repeat his work here, but merely set forth the reasons behind these names.
  footnotes:
    - The phrase 'thirty-six renowned peaks' (三十六洞) refers to the mythical Daoist paradises, suggesting the garden contains the essence of natural perfection.
    - The hexagram Tai (泰) from the I Ching represents a state of universal harmony and communication between opposite forces—heaven and earth, ruler and subject—making it an apt name for a space that reconciles worldly duty with spiritual tranquility.
